"1177–1250":"1177–1250","1165–1250":"1165–1250","1170–1265":"1170–1265","1175–1213":"1175–1213","1205–1258":"1205–1258","1145–1248":"1145–1248","1145–1205":"1145–1205","1205":"1205","1248":"1248","1258":"1258","1213":"1213","1145":"1145","1177":"1177","1265":"1265","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1170":"1170","Dundonald, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dundonald, Ayrshire, Scotland","Crawford, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Crawford, Lanarkshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Crawford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: habitational name from any of various places called Crawford, primarily the one in Lanarkshire (Scotland), and possibly also from the one in Lancashire. Both are named in Old English with <i>crāwe</i> ‘crow’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."],"variants":[{"name":"Crafford","meanings":["English (Cumberland) and Scottish: variant of   Crawford  ."]},{"name":"Crofoot","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Crawford  .","English: variant of<b>Crowfoot</b>, a nickname for someone with splayed feet or someother deformity of the foot, from Old English <i>crāwe</i> ‘crow’ +<i>fōt</i> ‘foot’. In Middle English <i>crou-fot</i> also denotedthe buttercup, and it may be from this sense that the name arose,although the reason for its adoption is unclear."]},{"name":"Crofut","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Crawford   or <b>Crowfoot</b> (see   Crofoot  )."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret De Crawford was born in 1177, in Dundonald, Ayrshire, Scotland, her father, Sir John de Crawford, was 32 and her mother, Margaret de Huntington -, was 32. She had at least 1 daughter with William \"Long Legs\" De Douglas. She died in 1250, at the age of 73."},"et":{"1177–1250":"1177–1250","1165–1250":"1165–1250","1170–1265":"1170–1265","1175–1213":"1175–1213","1205–1258":"1205–1258","1145–1248":"1145–1248","1145–1205":"1145–1205","1205":"1205","1248":"1248","1258":"1258","1213":"1213","1145":"1145","1177":"1177","1265":"1265","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1170":"1170","Dundonald, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dundonald, Ayrshire, Scotland","Crawford, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Crawford, Lanarkshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1177–1250":"1177–1250","1165–1250":"1165–1250","1170–1265":"1170–1265","1175–1213":"1175–1213","1205–1258":"1205–1258","1145–1248":"1145–1248","1145–1205":"1145–1205","1205":"1205","1248":"1248","1258":"1258","1213":"1213","1145":"1145","1177":"1177","1265":"1265","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1170":"1170","Dundonald, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dundonald, Ayrshire, Scotland","Crawford, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Crawford, Lanarkshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1177–1250":"1177–1250","1165–1250":"1165–1250","1170–1265":"1170–1265","1175–1213":"1175–1213","1205–1258":"1205–1258","1145–1248":"1145–1248","1145–1205":"1145–1205","1205":"1205","1248":"1248","1258":"1258","1213":"1213","1145":"1145","1177":"1177","1265":"1265","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1